article.description: Jia Perkins had 20 points, and second-ranked Texas Tech scored on 14 straight first-half possessions in a 95-47 victory Tuesday night over San Diego in the championship game of the Surf-N-Slam Classic.
article.headline: Perkins leads balanced attack
article.linkText: Lady Raiders improve to 13-0 with rout of San Diego
article.story:
SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Texas Tech bounced back from one of its
sloppiest games with a convincing win.

Jia Perkins had 20 points, and No. 2 Texas Tech scored on 14
straight first-half possessions, in a 95-47 victory Tuesday night
over San Diego in the championship game of the Surf-N-Slam Classic.

The Lady Raiders (13-0) had their worse shooting game of the
season and tied their season high with 19 turnovers in a 65-53 win
over Maryland on Sunday in the first round of the tournament.

On Tuesday, Texas Tech ran at will en route to a 50-25 halftime
lead.

"I think we wanted to come out there and prove that we are a
good team and can play very well," Perkins said.

Texas Tech made an emphatic statement in the first 20 minutes,
shooting 59.5 percent from the field. The Lady Raiders scored on 14
straight possessions to increase a 10-4 lead nearly six minutes
into the game into a 38-11 advantage at the 6:41 mark.

"I thought the middle 10 minutes of the first half was the best
we've played overall this year," Texas Tech coach Marsha Sharp
said.

San Diego (5-7) tried to run with Texas Tech, but had a
difficult time. The Toreros missed 24 of their first 28 shots and
were outrebounded 29-12 in the first half.

"We wanted to run, but we just aren't as good at it as they
are," Toreros coach Kathy Marpe said. "They were a lot quicker
than I thought."

Texas Tech extended its school record for consecutive wins to
begin a season. The Lady Raiders also won their third consecutive
tournament this season.

"I think we looked like a great team when we get that
momentum," Perkins said.

Perkins made nine of 12 shots to lead a balanced Lady Raiders
attack in which 11 players scored. Perkins was chosen as the
tournament's Most Valuable Player.

Jametra Clark scored 15 points and Alesha Robertson went 5-for-5
from the field to score 14 points for Texas Tech, which shot 58
percent. Cisti Greenwalt added 12 points and 10 rebounds.

"Coach told us we had to come back strong," Robertson said.
"Our transition game helped us out a lot tonight, and that made the
game a lot easier."

Marta Menuez scored 11 points for San Diego, a loser for the
first time in four games.

The Toreros made only 18 of 65 shots from the floor (27.7
percent) and were outrebounded 53-24.

San Diego had played tough in its last two home games against
ranked teams, losing by two points in overtime to No. 4 Iowa State
in December 2001 and by two points in double overtime to
16th-ranked Oklahoma in December 2000.
